         <abstract>
            <p>Most companies sell convertible debentures to raise equity capital at a premium price. But a convertible cannot be called to force its holders to convert into equity until its conversion value is higher than the call price. Meanwhile it remains a debt security, and may interfere with the issuer's ability to raise other forms of needed long-term capital. The recent record suggests that a substantial time period frequently elapses before an issuer can safely force conversion with a call.</p>
          </abstract>
